      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Minor Repairs and Emergency Fixes During a Brisbane Sale Campaign
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Over a four to eight week campaign, things break. Appliances fail, plumbing leaks, lights stop working, and sometimes more significant items go wrong. Here is how to triage what to fix, what to disclose, and what to leave.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The reality of a four to eight week Brisbane sale campaign is that things will break. Appliances fail, plumbing leaks appear, light fittings stop working, sometimes more significant items go wrong (a hot water system gives up, a deck board cracks, a storm causes minor damage). Each issue forces the seller into a small decision: fix it, disclose it, or leave it. Most sellers handle these decisions instinctively, and most of the time they handle them reasonably well. But the campaign-period decisions that go wrong tend to go wrong in the same predictable ways, and the fixes are not complicated once you have a framework.</p>

      <p>The legal baseline is straightforward. The seller's obligation under the standard REIQ contract is to deliver the property in the same condition as at exchange, fair wear and tear excepted. This means the campaign-period condition matters, not just the original listing condition. What was working at exchange should still be working at settlement, or the seller should have notified the buyer and adjusted accordingly. The framework below sits inside that legal baseline and gives you a practical way to handle issues as they appear.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Category 1: Fix immediately</h2>
      <p>Anything affecting safety should be fixed immediately, regardless of cost or campaign timing. Broken steps, exposed wiring, gas leaks, faulty smoke alarms, or anything that could cause injury at an open home or to the seller in the meantime sits in this category. The exposure from leaving safety issues unfixed is large and the cost of fixing them is almost always small relative to that exposure.</p>

      <p>Anything affecting essential utilities should also be fixed immediately. No hot water, blocked drains, no power to a room, water leaks of any kind. Buyers viewing a property where essential systems are not working form an immediate negative impression that is very hard to recover, and the seller's obligation under the contract is to deliver these systems working.</p>

      <p>Anything visible at open homes or photos should be fixed before the next inspection. Cracked tiles, broken light fittings, peeling paint, smashed window panes, damaged blinds. Visible defects discount the property in buyer perception by far more than the cost of repair, and negotiation leverage shifts to the buyer the moment they see something obvious that has not been addressed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Category 2: Fix before settlement, disclose now</h2>
      <p>Some non-urgent issues emerge during the campaign that do not need immediate attention but need to be disclosed and resolved before settlement. A failed dishwasher, a deck board that needs replacement, a fan motor making noise, a non-essential appliance that has stopped working. These items can be fixed in time for the pre-settlement inspection without disrupting open homes, but the buyer's solicitor should be notified promptly so the issue is on the record and the resolution can be tracked.</p>

      <p>Communicate promptly with the buyer's solicitor. The longer an issue sits undisclosed, the more it looks evasive when it surfaces. Buyers who learn about a campaign-period issue at the pre-settlement inspection (rather than from the seller earlier) tend to assume there are other things they have not been told about, and the negotiation tone deteriorates from there.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Category 3: Disclose, do not fix</h2>
      <p>Some issues were present at exchange and the buyer has accepted them as part of the property. Ageing systems with finite remaining life that the buyer expects to replace anyway, structural items requiring expert assessment beyond simple repair, or known defects that were disclosed pre-contract and priced into the offer. These do not need to be fixed during the campaign and attempting to do so can introduce new risks (a partial repair that creates a worse defect, work that triggers warranty obligations, expense that the buyer was already factoring as their problem).</p>

      <p>Document the condition at exchange with photos and inspection reports, and do not let the property's condition deteriorate further during the campaign. The disclose-only category is for issues that were already known and accepted, not for issues that emerge during the campaign and could be quietly left for the buyer to discover.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What 'fair wear and tear' actually covers</h2>
      <p>Fair wear and tear is the legal exception to the same-condition obligation, and it is narrower than most sellers assume. It covers ordinary deterioration from normal use over short periods. Examples include minor scuff marks, gradual paint fading, light corrosion on outdoor fixtures, and the routine wear of carpets and tapware that comes from being used. It does not cover damage from accidents (someone drops a heavy item on the floor), from neglect (failure to maintain a system that then fails), or from storms (storm damage is its own category, see below). When in doubt, treat the issue as not covered by fair wear and tear and handle it through the categories above.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The storm damage scenario</h2>
      <p>If a major storm causes damage during the campaign (which is more common in Brisbane than in many capital cities, particularly in the late summer and early autumn months), the typical resolution is through the seller's home and contents insurance. Notify the insurer as soon as the damage is identified. Notify the buyer's solicitor immediately. Document everything with photos and a written description of what happened, when, and what the immediate response was.</p>

      <p>Maintain active home insurance throughout the campaign, including the period between exchange and settlement. Some sellers cancel insurance after exchange in the belief that the buyer is now responsible. The buyer is responsible for risk under the standard contract, but the seller is still responsible for delivering the property in the same condition as at exchange, and uninsured storm damage during this window can become an expensive dispute.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The appliance failure scenario</h2>
      <p>If a fridge, oven, dishwasher, or air conditioning unit fails during the campaign, and the appliance is included in the sale, the seller's obligation is to repair or replace before settlement. For a relatively new appliance, repair or like-for-like replacement is usually the cleanest path. For an aged unit that was already near end of life, a price adjustment in lieu of replacement may be the more practical resolution, agreed in writing with the buyer's solicitor.</p>

      <p>Document the failure, the response, and the resolution in writing. Verbal agreements about appliance replacement and price adjustments tend to drift in interpretation between exchange and settlement, and a written record protects both parties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The budget for typical campaign-period repairs</h2>
      <p>Plan a modest contingency of $1,500-$3,000 for a typical Brisbane home over a six to eight week campaign. This covers the small-to-medium issues that tend to surface (a tap washer, a tripped circuit, a fence panel, a minor leak, a broken sensor light) without forcing a budget conversation each time. For older homes (pre-1980 or pre-renovation properties), a higher contingency of $3,000-$5,000 is more realistic, because more items are at end of life and minor issues compound through the campaign period.</p>

      <p>Treat the contingency as a campaign cost, not as an unexpected expense. Properties do not pause their physical condition while a sale is in progress, and the budget for keeping them in condition is a normal part of campaign planning.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NOT to do</h2>
      <p>Do not delay disclosing significant issues until pre-settlement. The longer an issue sits undisclosed, the more evasive it looks when it eventually surfaces, and the weaker the seller's negotiating position becomes when it does. Buyers who feel they have been managed rather than informed tend to push harder on every other point in the settlement.</p>

      <p>Do not over-promise repairs that may not be completed in time for settlement. If a pre-settlement repair is genuinely required, use a written variation of contract that records exactly what will be done, by whom, by when, and with what evidence (a contractor invoice, a compliance certificate, a photograph of the completed work). Verbal commitments to "have it sorted before settlement" are a regular source of disputes when something slips.</p>

      <p>Do not assume issues will go unnoticed at the pre-settlement inspection. Buyers (or their inspectors) check what is working, look in the cupboards, run the appliances, flick the lights, test the taps. Issues that the seller hoped would not be spotted are usually spotted, and being caught is far worse for the negotiating position than disclosure would have been.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The documentation</h2>
      <p>Keep written records of any campaign-period repairs. Receipts, contractor reports, before-and-after photos, dates of work, names of who did the work. Include these in the property pack handed over at settlement. This builds buyer confidence in the property and in the seller's diligence, and it supports the asking price by demonstrating active care of the asset through the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Treat campaign-period maintenance as an active responsibility, not a passive one. When something breaks, run it through the safety, utility, and visible categories first; if any of those apply, fix immediately. If not, decide between fix-before-settlement-with-disclosure and disclose-without-fixing based on whether the issue was present at exchange. Communicate honestly and promptly with buyers about anything material. Issues handled openly are rarely deal killers in Brisbane sales; issues hidden often are. The contingency budget exists precisely so the campaign can absorb routine maintenance without the seller losing focus or making a poor decision under pressure. Plan for it, and the campaign-period repairs become a footnote rather than a problem.</p>

